This was the long period of com- parative quiet between the Gracchan disturbances (Β. c. 133-121) and the tribunate of Drusus (Β. c. 91, see note, ξ 9), followed by the Social War and the civil wars of Marius and Sulla—Latio: not the geographical Latium merely, but including all‘towns which at that time possessed Latin citizenship ; that is, the Latin colonies, such as Venusia, the birth-place of the poet Horace.

Colonies sent out by Rome were of two classes: 1. Romen colones, in which a small garrison of soldiere (usually 300 in numberiwas established as a governing aristocracy. The native population was held by them in a harsh subjection. 2. Latin cotonies. in which the colonists‚ whether native Romans or not, formeria quasi-independent conr- munity. They were usually quite numerous, went with their families, and did not possess Roman citizenship; but. on the other hand, the right of coining money and other rights of sovereignty. These Latin colonies, together with the original Letins, formed the nomen Latinum, and stood towards Rome in the relation os civitates soederntoe. Therefore
